                            <container4
                                cq:styleIds="[1653545825686,1653545847150,1653242825678,1653545835982,1653545835879]"
                                jcr:lastModified="{Date}2025-12-05T11:44:53.956-05:00"
                                jcr:lastModifiedBy="singarx"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/container/v2/container"
                                dmPresetType="imagePreset">
                                <text
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2025-12-05T11:46:18.493-05:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="singarx"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2025-12-10T08:47:24.002-05:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="singarx"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>New medicines offer innovative and more effective treatments that can improve the health and lives of all Australians. But delays in medicines being listed on the Pharmaceutical Benefits Scheme (PBS) are getting longer. Increasingly, new medicines are failing to make it to Australia altogether despite being available in other countries.1&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>&lt;b>Did you know?&lt;/b>&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;ul>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;li>Australia ranks&amp;nbsp;&lt;b>16th out of 20 OECD countries&lt;/b>&amp;nbsp;for the number of reimbursed new medicines via the PBS.2&lt;/li>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;li>Australia ranks&amp;nbsp;&lt;b>25th out of 33 countries&lt;/b>&amp;nbsp;in terms of medicines spending as a percentage of the health budget.3&lt;/li>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;/ul>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>The PBS has been a cornerstone of Australia’s public health system for 75 years, providing Australians with affordable access to medicines. But it is not keeping pace with leaps forward in innovation.&amp;nbsp; The way medicines are evaluated for inclusion on the PBS has not had system-level change in more than 30 years.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
                            </container4>
                        </par_12>
